<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06021071 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06021071 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  ARIZONA; LABOR; ORGANIZATION; FARM; VEGETABLE; COMPANY; BAN; COURT; RULING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The United Farm Workers of America and lettuce grower Bruce Church Inc. ofSalinas said their fight continues despite an Arizona appeals court decisionto void a $5.4 million judgment against the union.;    Church, the nation'ssecond-largest lettuce producer, won the award in 1988 when a Superior Courtjury in Yuma, Ariz., concluded the union had caused &quot;unjustified harm&quot; to thecompany by pushing boycotts of stores selling Church lettuce.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business Monday  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  UFW WINS BOYCOTT CASE APPEAL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Labor  </MEMO><TEXT>     Union officials said the Arizona ruling last week represents vindicationand eliminates a huge penalty.;    &quot;It confirms that we were right,&quot; saidDavid Martinez, UFW secretary-treasurer at union headquarters in Keene. &quot;(But)it is not going to get us a contract.&quot;;    The case centers on the union'smost trusted weapon, the boycott, which also is the focus of growers' mostbitter criticism.;    The technique -- the so-called secondary boycott -- isoutlawed by Arizona farm labor law. It is also the UFW's key weapon in tryingto win contracts from growers.;    The Court of Appeals in Phoenix found thatUFW boycotting activities had taken place in California, not Arizona, and thatthe Arizona law could not extend beyond state borders.;    It also found thatmost activities that Bruce complained about were &quot;pure speech&quot; protected bythe First Amendment, said UFW lawyer Dianna Lyons.;    The court ordered theBruce-UFW case back to trial court but only to decide on the company'scontention that union activities interfered with the company's businessactivities and contracts.;    Yuma attorney Jim Clark, representing Church,said the company may appeal or may return to trial on the business activitiesand contracts allegation.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  McClatchy News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Fresno  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910121  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  267  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday January 21, 199100021071,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>